<Author>duboce
<Content>The best part of staying at the Comfort Inn The best part of staying at the Comfort Inn was coming back to this web site and reading the bozo review (mostly from Europeans) who have criticized and posted here. I spent 1 week and would like to tell you about it. I arrived in Boston, got my Hertz Rental car and drove with map instructions to the hotel. I had a difficult time finding the place because the area has had major highway construction and rerouting of lanes. The work is finished but it really takes a skilled driver to find the place the first few times. The street in front of the hotel is divided and you can cross either by foot over the bridge, or on the street (dangerous to do so) if you want to go to the supermarket across the street. Use the bridge, save yourself.  Check in was fine and my room was above expectations. I used the shuttle the following day to go to the airport to retrieve people arriving from Japan and coming back was fine except that on using the shuttles, I noticed that each driver had a different way to get to and from the hotel. Unless you really need a car, don't bother renting one. Follow the instructions in the lobby and use the shuttle to the T (subway stop) pay $2 and go in town. Its easy, fast and you don't have to deal with the car.  Dining: The hotel has a free continental breakfast. There is a microwave in the dining room and you can use it for the oatmeal or hot cereal, hot chocolate, etc. or microwave your own food (at any hour you wish). The dining room provides make your own waffles, scrambled eggs, the usual cakes, toast, rolls, juices. Its not a big dining room but the European tourists that overloaded the hotel thought they were at a sidewalk cafe and the lines waiting to eat were annoying due to many people sitting and reading a paper while having breakfast. Generally it is sufficient, clean, and filling. There is no other dining option at the hotel. You can walk about 1 block to the bowling alley where there is an Italian sandwich shop and pizza, adequate but nothing great. Just okay from my point of view. Next to it is that Phillips Candy shop. At $23 a pound they don't give out samples and the employees act as if they are the owners of the place and keep count of every item. Next to it is the restaurant/bar. Its worth going to. They have a good menu, its like an English pub, many beers and cocktails, good service, the waitresses are patient and helpful especially in dealing with the tourists who did not speak English. I would go back there again even if not staying at the hotel. 4**** for the restaurant. The pool at the Marriot is available for use but I never saw anybody using it. You would have to carry your suit and towel there, walking 1 block or driving over there if you want to go for a swim. The noise factor from the T is not that bad. Maybe it is if you are in the rear of the hotel but the front was quite nice and there is plenty of free parking. The rooms have an iron and an ironing board and there is a laundry on the first floor. You can wash and dry clothes and the washer has an automatic soap dispenser which adds soap and fabric softner so you don't have to worry about obtaining it at all. Some of the staff on the front desk were not too bright and gave me directions which caused me to get lost while looking for a Target store. Others on the front desk are quite competent and accomodating. You can sit in the lobby or in the front of the hotel and have a cigarette and read a newspaper. Most of the guests were in and out all day long. This hotel is not really close in at all but the alternative is staying in central Boston at a much higher rate and generally in a dumpy downtown area. Boston is congested and not that clean in my opinion. The cleaning staff at the Comfort Inn did a very good job, were thorough and efficient. I am always amazed at the slobs who criticize here. Just take a walk through the hallways and look into the rooms that the maids are cleaning. Clothes on the food, bottles all over and debris in the room. These are the slobs that call everything filthy and post it here. Take a good look at the full length mirror and see who the slobs really are. I notice that many Europeans are critical when writing reviews. The very same people who camp in downtown areas in European parks and wear lederhosen or sweat outfits to fancy restaurants seem to think they are in Monte Carlo (playing the lowest denomination slot machine). I would recommend the hotel and would stay there, had no complaints for the 7 days we were there. Thank you . 
