<Author>thaus76
<Content>Good experience Let me first say that I am rating this hotel as compared to other hotels of similar caliber. As a 3-star hotel, I felt that the Comfort Inn was a very good value. It was certainly priced well below other hotels of similar ranking in the area, and the free parking, free continental breakfast, and free shuttle to the subway probably saved us another $50/day over hotels in Boston's downtown areas. The front desk staff was courteous, and since we arrived late in the evening they gave us a free room upgrade as the last available room was between the elevator and ice machine, and the hotel staff did not want to put us there (nice of them, I thought.) The room was perfectly nice, nothing fancy but clean and tastefully decorated. The subway line runs behind the building, and can be noisy at night if you are a light sleeper so maybe request a room at the front of the hotel. The shuttle to the T station ran every half hour, and we never had an excessive wait. There really isn't anything nearby as far as restaurants or attractions (save for the on-property restaurants and bowling alley) so one pretty much has to get on the T to get to almost anything.The on-property restaurants were nice enough, although it depends on what your definintion of on-property is. It is about a 2 block walk to the Ramada Inn, which is where the restaurants, bowling alley, AND THE COMFORT INN's POOL are. The area seems safe enough during the day, but I was very nervous walking from the restaurant back to the hotel at night as the area is a bit industrial and not well lit. The walk is especially bothersome if you plan on using the pool, unless you want to take clothes with you and change at the Ramada. In fact, I never used the pool becuase of this inconvenience.The continental breakfast was very good. Belgian waffles, cereal, and bagels/muffins/ toast, and fruit if you get up early enough to get it. This hotel seems to cater to a very international and family-oriented crowd. But, if you have kids who want to use the entertainment complex you might want to consider the Ramada instead to eliminate the walk.Overall, I would recommend this hotel for anyone who wants a nice hotel at a good price. It is not the Ritz, but for a 3-star hotel it was more than adequate. 
